<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-455-855  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 455 855.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Sept 13 1990 v16 n18 p76(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Laser-disk filing system on the market. (Laser Access'Flash-Filer) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Laser Access (product introduction).andO;Product:   Laser Access Flash-Filer (Document processing system) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionLaser VideodiscDisk DrivesDocument Management SystemsImage Processing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Laser-disk filing system on the marketandM;RICHMOND HILL, Ont -- Laser Access announces its laser-disk document storageand retrieval system.andM;The Flash-Filer system can permanently store roughly the equivalent of up totwo four-drawer file cabinets on each disk, saving space and costs, and canretrieve any stored document to a computer display in as little as twoseconds.andM;The documents scanned into the system can be invoices, receipts, contracts,legal files, correspondence or anything on paper.andP;  Using optical disks whichcannot be overwritten by mistake or otherwise, the Flash-Filer system can beadded to an existing PC (DOS) or LAN or can be configured as a standalonesystem with numerous workstations.andM;Depending on the requirements, the system's hardware can vary from asingle-site PC/scanner/disk drive combination having a capacity of 15,000images per disk and ranges through to an addition to an existing networkserving unlimited users and storing more than five milion pages on a seriesof &quot;jukeboxes&quot; which automatically select disks for retrieval.andM;Add-on-to-PC, entry-level systems including auto-scanner, 650MB drive andportrait monitor begin at about $350 per month (on a lease) and $15,000(purchase).andP;  The software can run on DOS, Novell, 3Com and LANs which supportDOS workstations.andO;</TEXT></DOC>